# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: business-logic-flaws
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:business-logic-flaws/abuse-case-cheat-sheet] Reviewers have identified that abuse cases are rarely used in practice.
[src:business-logic-flaws/abuse-case-cheat-sheet] Additionally, the material is presented as a "getting started tutorial" which isn't appropriate for the cheat sheet series.
[src:business-logic-flaws/abuse-case-cheat-sheet] These security requirements are too generic, and thus useless for a development team...
[src:business-logic-flaws/abuse-case-cheat-sheet] In order to build a secure application, from a pragmatic point of view, it is important to identify the attacks which the application must defend against, according to its business and technical context.
[src:business-logic-flaws/abuse-case-cheat-sheet] Abuse cases were a frequently recommended *threat modeling* technique, and reviewing the threat modeling cheat sheet may be helpful.
[src:business-logic-flaws/abuse-case-cheat-sheet] In practice, the abuse case framework seems heavyweight and there are few published examples or success stories.
[src:business-logic-flaws/abuse-case-cheat-sheet] The cheat sheet may be used for this purpose regardless of the project methodology used (waterfall or agile).
[src:business-logic-flaws/abuse-case-cheat-sheet] You can think of **Abuse cases** in two ways.
[src:business-logic-flaws/abuse-case-cheat-sheet] The first is to discover attacks (answer the question "what can go wrong"), and the second is to help record those attacks (informally, this includes threats, issues, risks) in a form that may be less intimidating to developers.
[src:business-logic-flaws/abuse-case-cheat-sheet] There are many different ways to define the list of abuse cases for a feature (that can be mapped to a user story in agile projects).
[src:business-logic-flaws/abuse-case-cheat-sheet] Threat Modeling is a set of techniques for anticipating what can go wrong, and ensuring we do something about each identified possible scenario.
[src:business-logic-flaws/abuse-case-cheat-sheet] Taking each item on the list of "what are we going to do about it" and writing an abuse case may help your engineering teams process the output.
[src:business-logic-flaws/abuse-case-cheat-sheet] During this workshop (duration will depend on the size of the feature list, but 4 hours is a good start) all business features that will be part of the project or the sprint will be processed.
[src:business-logic-flaws/abuse-case-cheat-sheet] The output of the workshop will be a list of attacks (abuse cases) for all business features.
[src:business-logic-flaws/abuse-case-cheat-sheet] All abuse cases will have a risk rating that allows for filtering and prioritization.
[src:business-logic-flaws/abuse-case-cheat-sheet] It is important to take into account **Technical** and **Business** kind of abuse cases and mark them accordingly.
[src:business-logic-flaws/abuse-case-cheat-sheet] In agile projects, the definition workshop must be made after the meeting in which User Stories are included in a Sprint.
[src:business-logic-flaws/abuse-case-cheat-sheet] In waterfall projects, the definition workshop must be made when the business features to implement are identified and known by the business.
[src:business-logic-flaws/abuse-case-cheat-sheet] Each abuse case must have a unique identifier in order to allow tracking throughout the whole project/sprint (details about this point will be given in the proposal section).
[src:business-logic-flaws/abuse-case-cheat-sheet] An example of unique ID format can be **ABUSE_CASE_001**.
[src:business-logic-flaws/abuse-case-cheat-sheet] The proposal will focus on the output of the workshop explained in the previous section.
[src:business-logic-flaws/abuse-case-cheat-sheet] First, even if it seems obvious, the key business people must be sure to know, understand and be able to explain the business features that will be processed during the workshop.
[src:business-logic-flaws/abuse-case-cheat-sheet] Use the spreadsheet to review all the features.
[src:business-logic-flaws/abuse-case-cheat-sheet] Penetration testers propose and explain a set of attacks that they can perform against the feature.
[src:business-logic-flaws/abuse-case-cheat-sheet] Appsec proposes a countermeasure and a preferred set up location (infrastructure, network, code, design...).
[src:business-logic-flaws/abuse-case-cheat-sheet] Technical people give feedback about the feasibility of the proposed countermeasure.
[src:business-logic-flaws/abuse-case-cheat-sheet] Penetration testers use the CVSS v3 (or other standard) calculator to determine a risk rating.
[src:business-logic-flaws/abuse-case-cheat-sheet] Risk leaders should accept or modify the risk rating to determine the final risk score which accurately reflects the real business impact for the company.
[src:business-logic-flaws/abuse-case-cheat-sheet] Business, Risk, and Technical leaders should find a consensus and filter the list of abuses for the current feature to keep the ones that must be addressed, and then flag them accordingly in the *ABUSE CASES* sheet (**if risk is accepted then add a comment to explain why**).
[src:business-logic-flaws/abuse-case-cheat-sheet] The spreadsheet contains (at this stage) the list of all abuse cases that must be handled and, potentially (depending on the capacity) corresponding countermeasures.
[src:business-logic-flaws/abuse-case-cheat-sheet] Key technical people must evaluate the overhead in terms of expense/effort to take into account the countermeasure.
[src:business-logic-flaws/abuse-case-cheat-sheet] Using this way, it becomes possible (via some minor scripting) to identify where abuse cases are addressed.
[src:business-logic-flaws/abuse-case-cheat-sheet] Adding automated tests also allow teams to track the effectiveness of countermeasures against abuse cases and determine if the countermeasures are still in place during a maintenance or bug fixing phase of a project (to prevent accidental removal/disabling).
[src:business-logic-flaws/abuse-case-cheat-sheet] It is also useful when a Continuous Delivery approach is used, to ensure that all abuse cases protections are in place before opening access to the application.
[src:business-logic-flaws/abuse-case-cheat-sheet] The following section shows an example of derivation of Abuse Cases as User Stories, here using the OWASP TOP 10 as input source.
[src:business-logic-flaws/abuse-case-cheat-sheet] Almost any source of data can be an injection vector, environment variables, parameters, external and internal web services, and all types of users.
[src:business-logic-flaws/abuse-case-cheat-sheet] Injection flaws occur when an attacker can send hostile data to an interpreter.
[src:business-logic-flaws/abuse-case-cheat-sheet] Attackers have access to hundreds of millions of valid username and password combinations for credential stuffing, default administrative account lists, automated brute force, and dictionary attack tools.
[src:business-logic-flaws/abuse-case-cheat-sheet] Session management attacks are well understood, particularly in relation to unexpired session tokens.
[src:business-logic-flaws/abuse-case-cheat-sheet] As an attacker, I have access to hundreds of millions of valid username and password combinations for credential stuffing.
[src:business-logic-flaws/abuse-case-cheat-sheet] As an attacker, I have default administrative account lists, automated brute force, and dictionary attack tools I use against login areas of the application and support systems.
[src:business-logic-flaws/abuse-case-cheat-sheet] As an attacker, I manipulate session tokens using expired and fake tokens to gain access.
[src:business-logic-flaws/abuse-case-cheat-sheet] Rather than directly attacking crypto, attackers steal keys, execute man-in-the-middle attacks, or steal clear text data off the server, while in transit, or from the user's client, e.g. browser.
[src:business-logic-flaws/abuse-case-cheat-sheet] Previously retrieved password databases could be brute forced by Graphics Processing Units (GPUs).
[src:business-logic-flaws/abuse-case-cheat-sheet] As an attacker, I steal keys that were exposed in the application to get unauthorized access to the application or system.
[src:business-logic-flaws/abuse-case-cheat-sheet] As an attacker, I execute man-in-the-middle attacks to get access to traffic and leverage it to obtain sensitive data and possibly get unauthorized access to the application.
[src:business-logic-flaws/abuse-case-cheat-sheet] As an attacker, I steal clear text data off the server, while in transit, or from the user's client, e.g. browser to get unauthorized access to the application or system.
[src:business-logic-flaws/abuse-case-cheat-sheet] As an attacker, I find and target old or weak cryptographic algorithms by capturing traffic and breaking the encryption.
[src:business-logic-flaws/abuse-case-cheat-sheet] Attackers can exploit vulnerable XML processors if they can upload XML or include hostile content in an XML document, exploiting vulnerable code, dependencies or integrations.
[src:business-logic-flaws/abuse-case-cheat-sheet] As an attacker, I exploit vulnerable areas of the application where the user or system can upload XML to extract data, execute a remote request from the server, scan internal systems, perform a denial-of-service attack, as well as execute other attacks.
[src:business-logic-flaws/abuse-case-cheat-sheet] As an attacker, I include hostile content in an XML document which is uploaded to the application or system to extract data, execute a remote request from the server, scan internal systems, perform a denial-of-service attack, as well as execute other attacks.
[src:business-logic-flaws/abuse-case-cheat-sheet] As an attacker, I include malicious XML code to exploit vulnerable code, dependencies or integrations to extract data, execute a remote request from the server, scan internal systems, perform a denial-of-service attack (e.g.
[src:business-logic-flaws/abuse-case-cheat-sheet] Billion Laughs attack), as well as execute other attacks.
[src:business-logic-flaws/abuse-case-cheat-sheet] Exploitation of access control is a core skill of attackers.
[src:business-logic-flaws/abuse-case-cheat-sheet] Access control is detectable using manual means, or possibly through automation for the absence of access controls in certain frameworks.
[src:business-logic-flaws/abuse-case-cheat-sheet] As an attacker, I bypass access control checks by modifying the URL, internal application state, or the HTML page, or simply using a custom API attack tool.
[src:business-logic-flaws/abuse-case-cheat-sheet] As an attacker, I manipulate the primary key and change it to access another's users record, allowing viewing or editing someone else's account.
[src:business-logic-flaws/abuse-case-cheat-sheet] As an attacker, I manipulate sessions, access tokens, or other access controls in the application to act as a user without being logged in, or acting as an admin/privileged user when logged in as a user.
[src:business-logic-flaws/abuse-case-cheat-sheet] As an attacker, I leverage metadata manipulation, such as replaying or tampering with a JSON Web Token (JWT) access control token or a cookie or hidden field manipulated to elevate privileges or abusing JWT invalidation.
[src:business-logic-flaws/abuse-case-cheat-sheet] As an attacker, I exploit Cross-Origin Resource Sharing CORS misconfiguration allowing unauthorized API access.
[src:business-logic-flaws/abuse-case-cheat-sheet] As an attacker, I force browsing to authenticated pages as an unauthenticated user or to privileged pages as a standard user.
[src:business-logic-flaws/abuse-case-cheat-sheet] As an attacker, I access APIs with missing access controls for POST, PUT and DELETE.
[src:business-logic-flaws/abuse-case-cheat-sheet] As an attacker, I target default crypto keys in use, weak crypto keys generated or re-used, or keys where rotation is missing.
[src:business-logic-flaws/abuse-case-cheat-sheet] As an attacker, I find areas where the user agent (e.g. app, mail client) does not verify if the received server certificate is valid and perform attacks where I get unauthorized access to data.
[src:business-logic-flaws/abuse-case-cheat-sheet] Attackers will often attempt to exploit unpatched flaws or access default accounts, unused pages, unprotected files and directories, etc to gain unauthorized access or knowledge of the system.
[src:business-logic-flaws/abuse-case-cheat-sheet] As an attacker, I find and exploit missing appropriate security hardening configurations on any part of the application stack, or improperly configured permissions on cloud services.
[src:business-logic-flaws/abuse-case-cheat-sheet] As an attacker, I find unnecessary features which are enabled or installed (e.g. unnecessary ports, services, pages, accounts, or privileges) and attack or exploit the weakness.
[src:business-logic-flaws/abuse-case-cheat-sheet] As an attacker, I use default accounts and their passwords to access systems, interfaces, or perform actions on components which I should not be able to.
[src:business-logic-flaws/abuse-case-cheat-sheet] As an attacker, I find areas of the application where error handling reveals stack traces or other overly informative error messages I can use for further exploitation.
[src:business-logic-flaws/abuse-case-cheat-sheet] As an attacker, I find areas where upgraded systems, latest security features are disabled or not configured securely.
[src:business-logic-flaws/abuse-case-cheat-sheet] As an attacker, I find security settings in the application servers, application frameworks (e.g.
[src:business-logic-flaws/abuse-case-cheat-sheet] Struts, Spring, ASP.NET), libraries, databases, etc. not set to secure values.
[src:business-logic-flaws/abuse-case-cheat-sheet] As an attacker, I find the server does not send security headers or directives or are set to insecure values.
[src:business-logic-flaws/abuse-case-cheat-sheet] XSS is the second most prevalent issue in the OWASP Top 10, and is found in around two-thirds of all applications.
[src:business-logic-flaws/abuse-case-cheat-sheet] As an attacker, I perform reflected XSS where the application or API includes unvalidated and unescaped user input as part of HTML output.
[src:business-logic-flaws/abuse-case-cheat-sheet] My successful attack can allow the attacker to execute arbitrary HTML and JavaScript in my victim's browser.
[src:business-logic-flaws/abuse-case-cheat-sheet] Typically the victim will need to interact with some malicious link that points to an attacker-controlled page, such as malicious watering hole websites, advertisements, or similar.
[src:business-logic-flaws/abuse-case-cheat-sheet] As an attacker, I perform stored XSS where the application or API stores unsanitized user input that is viewed at a later time by another user or an administrator.
[src:business-logic-flaws/abuse-case-cheat-sheet] As an attacker, I perform DOM XSS where JavaScript frameworks, single-page applications, and APIs that dynamically include attacker-controllable data to a page is vulnerable to DOM XSS.
[src:business-logic-flaws/abuse-case-cheat-sheet] Exploitation of deserialization is somewhat difficult, as off-the-shelf exploits rarely work without changes or tweaks to the underlying exploit code.
[src:business-logic-flaws/abuse-case-cheat-sheet] As an attacker, I find areas of the application and APIs where deserialization of hostile or tampered objects can be supplied.
[src:business-logic-flaws/abuse-case-cheat-sheet] As a result, I can focus on an object and data structure related attacks where the attacker modifies application logic or achieves arbitrary remote code execution if there are classes available to the application that can change behavior during or after deserialization.
[src:business-logic-flaws/abuse-case-cheat-sheet] Or I focus on data tampering attacks such as access-control-related attacks where existing data structures are used but the content is changed.
[src:business-logic-flaws/abuse-case-cheat-sheet] While it is easy to find already-written exploits for many known vulnerabilities, other vulnerabilities require concentrated effort to develop a custom exploit.
[src:business-logic-flaws/abuse-case-cheat-sheet] Exploitation of insufficient logging and monitoring is the bedrock of nearly every major incident.
[src:business-logic-flaws/abuse-case-cheat-sheet] Attackers rely on the lack of monitoring and timely response to achieve their goals without being detected.
[src:business-logic-flaws/abuse-case-cheat-sheet] In 2016, identifying a breach took an average of 191 days allowing substantial chance for damage to be inflicted.
[src:business-logic-flaws/abuse-case-cheat-sheet] As an attacker, I attack an organization and the logs, monitoring systems, and teams do not see or respond to my attacks.
[src:business-logic-flaws/abuse-case-cheat-sheet] All figures were created using https://www.draw.io/ site and exported (as PNG image) for integration into this article.
[src:business-logic-flaws/application-security] Web Application Security Tools are specialized tools for working with HTTP traffic, e.g., Web application firewalls.
[src:business-logic-flaws/application-security] Different approaches will find different subsets of the security vulnerabilities lurking in an application and are most effective at different times in the software lifecycle.
[src:business-logic-flaws/application-security] They each represent different tradeoffs of time, effort, cost and vulnerabilities found.
[src:business-logic-flaws/application-security] The Open Worldwide Application Security Project (OWASP) provides free and open resources.
[src:business-logic-flaws/application-security] It is led by a non-profit called The OWASP Foundation.
[src:business-logic-flaws/application-security] The OWASP Top 10 - 2017 results from recent research based on comprehensive data compiled from over 40 partner organizations.
[src:business-logic-flaws/application-security] This data revealed approximately 2.3 million vulnerabilities across over 50,000 applications.
[src:business-logic-flaws/application-security] The OWASP Top 10 Proactive Controls 2024 is a list of security techniques every software architect and developer should know and heed.
[src:business-logic-flaws/application-security] Security testing techniques scour for vulnerabilities or security holes in applications.
[src:business-logic-flaws/application-security] These vulnerabilities leave applications open to exploitation.
[src:business-logic-flaws/application-security] Ideally, security testing is implemented throughout the entire software development life cycle (SDLC) so that vulnerabilities may be addressed in a timely and thorough manner.
[src:business-logic-flaws/application-security] There are many kinds of automated tools for identifying vulnerabilities in applications.
[src:business-logic-flaws/business-logic-vulnerability] Most security problems are weaknesses in an application that result from a broken or missing security control (authentication, access control, input validation, etc…).
[src:business-logic-flaws/business-logic-vulnerability] By contrast, business logic vulnerabilities are ways of using the legitimate processing flow of an application in a way that results in a negative consequence to the organization.
[src:business-logic-flaws/business-logic-vulnerability] Many articles that describe business logic problems simply take an existing and well understood web application security problem and discuss the business consequence of the vulnerability.
[src:business-logic-flaws/business-logic-vulnerability] True business logic problems are actually different from the typical security vulnerability.
[src:business-logic-flaws/business-logic-vulnerability] Too often, the business logic category is used for vulnerabilities that can’t be scanned for automatically.
[src:business-logic-flaws/business-logic-vulnerability] This makes it very difficult to apply any kind of categorization scheme.
[src:business-logic-flaws/business-logic-vulnerability] Business logic problems are different from authentication problems and every other category.
[src:business-logic-flaws/business-logic-vulnerability] There are many signficant business logic vulnerabilities, but they are far less common than the type of items in the OWASP Top Ten for example.
[src:business-logic-flaws/business-logic-vulnerability] A nice rule-of-thumb to use is that if you need to truly understand the business to understand the vulnerability, you might have a business-logic problem on your hands.
[src:business-logic-flaws/business-logic-vulnerability] If you don’t understand the business, you can’t see business logic flaws.
[src:business-logic-flaws/business-logic-vulnerability] The likelihood of business logic problems really depends on the circumstances.
[src:business-logic-flaws/business-logic-vulnerability] You’ll need to evaluate the threat agents who could possibly exploit the problem and whether it would be detected.
[src:business-logic-flaws/business-logic-vulnerability] Again, this will take a strong understanding of the business.
[src:business-logic-flaws/business-logic-vulnerability] The vulnerabilities themselves are often quite easy to discover and exploit without any special tools or techniques, as they are a supported part of the application.
[src:business-logic-flaws/business-logic-vulnerability] Business logic flaws are often the most critical in terms of consequences, as they are deeply tied into the company’s process.
[src:business-logic-flaws/business-logic] In computer software, **business logic** or **domain logic** is the part of the program that encodes the real-world business rules that determine how data can be created, stored, and changed.
[src:business-logic-flaws/business-logic] It is contrasted with the remainder of the software that might be concerned with lower-level details of managing a database or displaying the user interface, system infrastructure, or generally connecting various parts of the program.
[src:business-logic-flaws/business-logic] Business logic should be distinguished from business rules.
[src:business-logic-flaws/business-logic] Business logic is the portion of an enterprise system which determines how data is transformed or calculated, and how it is routed to people or software (workflow).
[src:business-logic-flaws/business-logic] Business rules are formal expressions of business policy.
[src:business-logic-flaws/business-logic] Anything that is a process or procedure is business logic, and anything that is neither a process nor a procedure is a business rule.
[src:business-logic-flaws/business-logic] Welcoming a new visitor is a process (workflow) consisting of steps to be taken, whereas saying every new visitor must be welcomed is a business rule.
[src:business-logic-flaws/business-logic] Further, business logic is procedural whereas business rules are declarative.
[src:business-logic-flaws/business-logic] For example, an e-commerce website might allow visitors to add items to a shopping cart, specify a shipping address, and supply payment information.
[src:business-logic-flaws/business-logic] Business logic could be anywhere in a program.
[src:business-logic-flaws/business-logic] For example, given a certain format for an address, a database table could be created which has columns that correspond exactly to the fields specified in the business logic, and type checks added to make sure that no invalid data is added.
[src:business-logic-flaws/business-logic] For example, the set of allowable address formats might change when an online retailer starts shipping products to a new country.
[src:business-logic-flaws/business-logic] Thus it is often seen as desirable to make the code that implements the business logic relatively isolated, or loosely coupled.
[src:business-logic-flaws/business-logic] This makes it more likely that changes to business logic will require a small set of code changes, in only one part of the code.
[src:business-logic-flaws/business-logic] Distant but strongly coupled code also creates more of a risk that the programmer will only make some of the necessary changes and miss part of the system, leading to incorrect operation.
[src:business-logic-flaws/business-logic] A multitier architecture formalizes this decoupling by creating a **business logic layer** which is separate from other tiers or layers, such as the data access layer or service layer.
[src:business-logic-flaws/business-logic] Each layer "knows" only a minimal amount about the code in the other layers—just enough to accomplish necessary tasks.
[src:business-logic-flaws/business-logic] For example, in a model–view–controller paradigm, the controller and view layers might be made as small as possible, with all the business logic concentrated in the model.
[src:business-logic-flaws/business-logic] For example, with relatively simple business entities, a generic view and controller could access database objects which themselves contain all the relevant business logic about what formats they accept and what changes are possible (known as the database model).
[src:business-logic-flaws/business-logic] Some tiered schemes use either a distinct application layer or a service layer, or consider the business logic layer to be the same as one of those.
[src:business-logic-flaws/business-logic] Business logic can be extracted from procedural code using a business rule management system (BRMS).
[src:business-logic-flaws/business-logic] The business rules approach of software development uses BRMSs and enforces a very strong separation of business logic from other code.
[src:business-logic-flaws/business-logic] User interface management systems are another technology used to enforce a strong separation between business logic and other code.
[src:business-logic-flaws/business-logic] The magic pushbutton is considered an "anti-pattern": a technique that in this case creates undesirable constraints which make it difficult to code business logic in an easy-to-maintain way.
[src:business-logic-flaws/business-logic] A domain model is an abstract representation of the data storage types required by business rules.
[src:business-logic-flaws/finite-state-machine] In theoretical computer science, a **finite-state machine** (**FSM**) or **finite-state automaton** (**FSA**, plural: *automata*), **finite automaton**, or simply a **state machine**, is a mathematical model of computation.
[src:business-logic-flaws/finite-state-machine] It is an abstract machine that can be in exactly one of a finite number of *states* at any given time.
[src:business-logic-flaws/finite-state-machine] The FSM can change from one state to another in response to some inputs; the change from one state to another is called a *transition*.
[src:business-logic-flaws/finite-state-machine] An FSM is defined by a list of its states, its initial state, and the inputs that trigger each transition.
[src:business-logic-flaws/finite-state-machine] Finite-state machines are of two types—deterministic finite-state machines and non-deterministic finite-state machines.
[src:business-logic-flaws/finite-state-machine] For any non-deterministic finite-state machine, an equivalent deterministic one can be constructed.
[src:business-logic-flaws/finite-state-machine] The behavior of state machines can be observed in many devices in modern society that perform a predetermined sequence of actions depending on a sequence of events with which they are presented.
[src:business-logic-flaws/finite-state-machine] The finite-state machine has less computational power than some other models of computation such as the Turing machine.
[src:business-logic-flaws/finite-state-machine] The computational power distinction means there are computational tasks that a Turing machine can do but an FSM cannot.
[src:business-logic-flaws/finite-state-machine] This is because an FSM's memory is limited by the number of states it has.
[src:business-logic-flaws/finite-state-machine] A finite-state machine has the same computational power as a Turing machine that is restricted such that its head may only perform "read" operations, and always has to move from left to right.
[src:business-logic-flaws/finite-state-machine] FSMs are studied in the more general field of automata theory.
[src:business-logic-flaws/finite-state-machine] An example of a simple mechanism that can be modeled by a state machine is a turnstile.
[src:business-logic-flaws/finite-state-machine] A turnstile, used to control access to subways and amusement park rides, is a gate with three rotating arms at waist height, one across the entryway.
[src:business-logic-flaws/finite-state-machine] Initially the arms are locked, blocking the entry, preventing patrons from passing through.
[src:business-logic-flaws/finite-state-machine] Depositing a coin or token in a slot on the turnstile unlocks the arms, allowing a single customer to push through.
[src:business-logic-flaws/finite-state-machine] After the customer passes through, the arms are locked again until another coin is inserted.
[src:business-logic-flaws/finite-state-machine] Considered as a state machine, the turnstile has two possible states: *Locked* and *Unlocked*.
[src:business-logic-flaws/finite-state-machine] There are two possible inputs that affect its state: putting a coin in the slot (*coin*) and pushing the arm (*push*).
[src:business-logic-flaws/finite-state-machine] In the locked state, pushing on the arm has no effect; no matter how many times the input *push* is given, it stays in the locked state.
[src:business-logic-flaws/finite-state-machine] Putting a coin in – that is, giving the machine a *coin* input – shifts the state from *Locked* to *Unlocked*.
[src:business-logic-flaws/finite-state-machine] In the unlocked state, putting additional coins in has no effect; that is, giving additional *coin* inputs does not change the state.
[src:business-logic-flaws/finite-state-machine] A customer pushing through the arms gives a *push* input and resets the state to *Locked*.
[src:business-logic-flaws/finite-state-machine] The turnstile state machine can also be represented by a directed graph called a state diagram *(above)*.
[src:business-logic-flaws/finite-state-machine] Each state is represented by a node (*circle*).
[src:business-logic-flaws/finite-state-machine] Edges (*arrows*) show the transitions from one state to another.
[src:business-logic-flaws/finite-state-machine] Each arrow is labeled with the input that triggers that transition.
[src:business-logic-flaws/finite-state-machine] An input that doesn't cause a change of state (such as a *coin* input in the *Unlocked* state) is represented by a circular arrow returning to the original state.
[src:business-logic-flaws/finite-state-machine] The arrow into the *Locked* node from the black dot indicates it is the initial state.
[src:business-logic-flaws/finite-state-machine] A *state* is a description of the status of a system that is waiting to execute a *transition*.
[src:business-logic-flaws/finite-state-machine] A transition is a set of actions to be executed when a condition is fulfilled or when an event is received.
[src:business-logic-flaws/finite-state-machine] For example, when using an audio system to listen to the radio (the system is in the "radio" state), receiving a "next" stimulus results in moving to the next station.
[src:business-logic-flaws/finite-state-machine] When the system is in the "CD" state, the "next" stimulus results in moving to the next track.
[src:business-logic-flaws/finite-state-machine] Identical stimuli trigger different actions depending on the current state.
[src:business-logic-flaws/finite-state-machine] Several state-transition table types are used.
[src:business-logic-flaws/finite-state-machine] The most common representation is shown below: the combination of current state (e.g.
[src:business-logic-flaws/finite-state-machine] By itself, the table cannot completely describe the action, so it is common to use footnotes.
[src:business-logic-flaws/finite-state-machine] Other related representations may not have this limitation.
[src:business-logic-flaws/finite-state-machine] For example, an FSM definition including the full action's information is possible using state tables (see also virtual finite-state machine).
[src:business-logic-flaws/finite-state-machine] The Unified Modeling Language has a notation for describing state machines.
[src:business-logic-flaws/finite-state-machine] UML state machines overcome the limitations of traditional finite-state machines while retaining their main benefits.
[src:business-logic-flaws/finite-state-machine] UML state machines introduce the new concepts of hierarchically nested states and orthogonal regions, while extending the notion of actions.
[src:business-logic-flaws/finite-state-machine] UML state machines have the characteristics of both Mealy machines and Moore machines.
[src:business-logic-flaws/finite-state-machine] They support actions that depend on both the state of the system and the triggering event, as in Mealy machines, as well as entry and exit actions, which are associated with states rather than transitions, as in Moore machines.
[src:business-logic-flaws/finite-state-machine] SDL embeds basic data types called "Abstract Data Types", an action language, and an execution semantic in order to make the finite-state machine executable.
[src:business-logic-flaws/finite-state-machine] There are a large number of variants to represent an FSM such as the one in figure 3.
[src:business-logic-flaws/finite-state-machine] In addition to their use in modeling reactive systems presented here, finite-state machines are significant in many different areas, including electrical engineering, linguistics, computer science, philosophy, biology, mathematics, video game programming, and logic.
[src:business-logic-flaws/finite-state-machine] Finite-state machines are a class of automata studied in automata theory and the theory of computation.
[src:business-logic-flaws/finite-state-machine] In computer science, finite-state machines are widely used in modeling of application behavior (control theory), design of hardware digital systems, software engineering, compilers, network protocols, and computational linguistics.
[src:business-logic-flaws/finite-state-machine] Finite-state machines can be subdivided into acceptors, classifiers, transducers and sequencers.
[src:business-logic-flaws/finite-state-machine] A (possibly infinite) set of symbol sequences, called a formal language, is a regular language if there is some acceptor that accepts *exactly* that set.
[src:business-logic-flaws/finite-state-machine] For example, the set of binary strings with an even number of zeroes is a regular language (cf.
[src:business-logic-flaws/finite-state-machine] 5), while the set of all strings whose length is a prime number is not.
[src:business-logic-flaws/finite-state-machine] An acceptor could also be described as defining a language that would contain every string accepted by the acceptor but none of the rejected ones; that language is *accepted* by the acceptor.
[src:business-logic-flaws/finite-state-machine] By definition, the languages accepted by acceptors are the regular languages.
[src:business-logic-flaws/finite-state-machine] The problem of determining the language accepted by a given acceptor is an instance of the algebraic path problem—itself a generalization of the shortest path problem to graphs with edges weighted by the elements of an (arbitrary) semiring.
[src:business-logic-flaws/finite-state-machine] An example of an accepting state appears in Fig.
[src:business-logic-flaws/finite-state-machine] 5: a deterministic finite automaton (DFA) that detects whether the binary input string contains an even number of 0s.
[src:business-logic-flaws/finite-state-machine] The FSM uses only entry actions, i.e., output depends only on state.
[src:business-logic-flaws/finite-state-machine] The advantage of the Moore model is a simplification of the behaviour.
[src:business-logic-flaws/finite-state-machine] The state machine recognizes two commands: "command_open" and "command_close", which trigger state changes.
[src:business-logic-flaws/finite-state-machine] The entry action (E:) in state "Opening" starts a motor opening the door, the entry action in state "Closing" starts a motor in the other direction closing the door.
[src:business-logic-flaws/finite-state-machine] States "Opened" and "Closed" stop the motor when fully opened or closed.
[src:business-logic-flaws/finite-state-machine] They signal to the outside world (e.g., to other state machines) the situation: "door is open" or "door is closed".
[src:business-logic-flaws/finite-state-machine] The FSM also uses input actions, i.e., output depends on input and state.
[src:business-logic-flaws/finite-state-machine] The use of a Mealy FSM leads often to a reduction of the number of states.
[src:business-logic-flaws/finite-state-machine] There are two input actions (I:): "start motor to close the door if command_close arrives" and "start motor in the other direction to open the door if command_open arrives".
[src:business-logic-flaws/finite-state-machine] The "opening" and "closing" intermediate states are not shown.
[src:business-logic-flaws/finite-state-machine] A further distinction is between *deterministic* (DFA) and *non-deterministic* (NFA, GNFA) automata.
[src:business-logic-flaws/finite-state-machine] In a deterministic automaton, every state has exactly one transition for each possible input.
[src:business-logic-flaws/finite-state-machine] In a non-deterministic automaton, an input can lead to one, more than one, or no transition for a given state.
[src:business-logic-flaws/finite-state-machine] The powerset construction algorithm can transform any nondeterministic automaton into a (usually more complex) deterministic automaton with identical functionality.
[src:business-logic-flaws/finite-state-machine] A finite-state machine with only one state is called a "combinatorial FSM".
[src:business-logic-flaws/finite-state-machine] It only allows actions upon transition *into* a state.
[src:business-logic-flaws/finite-state-machine] This concept is useful in cases where a number of finite-state machines are required to work together, and when it is convenient to consider a purely combinatorial part as a form of FSM to suit the design tools.
[src:business-logic-flaws/finite-state-machine] There are other sets of semantics available to represent state machines.
[src:business-logic-flaws/finite-state-machine] For example, there are tools for modeling and designing logic for embedded controllers.
[src:business-logic-flaws/finite-state-machine] They combine hierarchical state machines (which usually have more than one current state), flow graphs, and truth tables into one language, resulting in a different formalism and set of semantics.
[src:business-logic-flaws/finite-state-machine] These charts, like Harel's original state machines, support hierarchically nested states, orthogonal regions, state actions, and transition actions.
[src:business-logic-flaws/finite-state-machine] In accordance with the general classification, the following formal definitions are found.
[src:business-logic-flaws/finite-state-machine] For both deterministic and non-deterministic FSMs, it is conventional to allow $\delta$ to be a partial function, i.e. $\delta (s,x)$ does not have to be defined for every combination of $s\in S$ and $x\in \Sigma$ .
[src:business-logic-flaws/finite-state-machine] If an FSM M is in a state s , the next symbol is x and $\delta (s,x)$ is not defined, then M can announce an error (i.e. reject the input).
[src:business-logic-flaws/finite-state-machine] This is useful in definitions of general state machines, but less useful when transforming the machine.
[src:business-logic-flaws/finite-state-machine] Some algorithms in their default form may require total functions.
[src:business-logic-flaws/finite-state-machine] That is, each formal language accepted by a finite-state machine is accepted by such a kind of restricted Turing machine, and vice versa.
[src:business-logic-flaws/finite-state-machine] If the output function depends on the state and input symbol ( $\omega :S\times \Sigma \rightarrow \Gamma$ ) that definition corresponds to the *Mealy model*, and can be modelled as a Mealy machine.
[src:business-logic-flaws/finite-state-machine] If the output function depends only on the state ( $\omega :S\rightarrow \Gamma$ ) that definition corresponds to the *Moore model*, and can be modelled as a Moore machine.
[src:business-logic-flaws/finite-state-machine] A finite-state machine with no output function at all is known as a semiautomaton or transition system.
[src:business-logic-flaws/finite-state-machine] If we disregard the first output symbol of a Moore machine, $\omega (s_{0})$ , then it can be readily converted to an output-equivalent Mealy machine by setting the output function of every Mealy transition (i.e. labeling every edge) with the output symbol given of the destination Moore state.
[src:business-logic-flaws/finite-state-machine] The converse transformation is less straightforward because a Mealy machine state may have different output labels on its incoming transitions (edges).
[src:business-logic-flaws/finite-state-machine] Every such state needs to be split in multiple Moore machine states, one for every incident output symbol.
[src:business-logic-flaws/finite-state-machine] Optimizing an FSM means finding a machine with the minimum number of states that performs the same function.
[src:business-logic-flaws/finite-state-machine] The fastest known algorithm doing this is the Hopcroft minimization algorithm.
[src:business-logic-flaws/finite-state-machine] Other techniques include using an implication table, or the Moore reduction procedure.
[src:business-logic-flaws/finite-state-machine] Additionally, acyclic FSAs can be minimized in linear time.
[src:business-logic-flaws/finite-state-machine] In a digital circuit, an FSM may be built using a programmable logic device, a programmable logic controller, logic gates and flip flops or relays.
[src:business-logic-flaws/finite-state-machine] More specifically, a hardware implementation requires a register to store state variables, a block of combinational logic that determines the state transition, and a second block of combinational logic that determines the output of an FSM.
[src:business-logic-flaws/finite-state-machine] In a *Medvedev machine*, the output is directly connected to the state flip-flops minimizing the time delay between flip-flops and output.
[src:business-logic-flaws/finite-state-machine] Through state encoding for low power state machines may be optimized to minimize power consumption.
[src:business-logic-flaws/finite-state-machine] Finite automata are often used in the frontend of programming language compilers.
[src:business-logic-flaws/finite-state-machine] Such a frontend may comprise several finite-state machines that implement a lexical analyzer and a parser.
[src:business-logic-flaws/finite-state-machine] Starting from a sequence of characters, the lexical analyzer builds a sequence of language tokens (such as reserved words, literals, and identifiers) from which the parser builds a syntax tree.
[src:business-logic-flaws/finite-state-machine] The lexical analyzer and the parser handle the regular and context-free parts of the programming language's grammar.
[src:business-logic-flaws/workflow] From a more abstract perspective, workflow may be considered a view or representation of real work.
[src:business-logic-flaws/workflow] The flow being described may refer to a document, service, or product that is being transferred from one step to another.
[src:business-logic-flaws/workflow] Workflows may be viewed as fundamental building blocks to be combined with other parts of an organization's structure, such as information technology, teams, projects, and hierarchies.
[src:business-logic-flaws/workflow] The development of the workflow concept occurred across several loosely defined, overlapping eras.
[src:business-logic-flaws/workflow] The modern history of workflows can be traced to Frederick Taylor and Henry Gantt, although the term "workflow" was not used in this context during their lifetimes.
[src:business-logic-flaws/workflow] One of the earliest instances of the term "work flow" was in a railway engineering journal from 1921.
[src:business-logic-flaws/workflow] Taylor and Gantt launched the study of the deliberate, rational organization of work, primarily in the context of manufacturing.
[src:business-logic-flaws/workflow] This gave rise to time and motion studies.
[src:business-logic-flaws/workflow] Related concepts include job shops and queuing systems (Markov chains).
[src:business-logic-flaws/workflow] The 1948 book *Cheaper by the Dozen* introduced the emerging workflow concept to the context of family life.
[src:business-logic-flaws/workflow] The invention of the typewriter and the copier helped spread the study of the rational organization of labor from the manufacturing shop floor to the office.
[src:business-logic-flaws/workflow] Filing and other sophisticated systems for managing physical information flows evolved.
[src:business-logic-flaws/workflow] Several events likely contributed to the development of formalized information workflows.
[src:business-logic-flaws/workflow] First, the field of optimization theory matured and developed mathematical optimization techniques.
[src:business-logic-flaws/workflow] For example, Soviet mathematician and economist Leonid Kantorovich developed the seeds of linear programming in 1939 through efforts to solve a plywood manufacturer's production optimization issues.
[src:business-logic-flaws/workflow] Second, World War II and the Apollo program drove process improvement forward with their demands for the rational organization of work.
[src:business-logic-flaws/workflow] Juran led to a focus on quality, first in Japanese companies, and more globally from the 1980s.
[src:business-logic-flaws/workflow] There were various movements ranging from total quality management to Six Sigma, and then more qualitative notions of business process re-engineering.
[src:business-logic-flaws/workflow] This led to more efforts to improve workflows in both knowledge economy sectors and manufacturing.
[src:business-logic-flaws/workflow] Thought leaders recognized variable demands on workflows when they considered the theory of critical paths and moving bottlenecks.
[src:business-logic-flaws/workflow] Basu and Kumar noted that the term "workflow management" referred to tasks associated with the flow of information through the value chain rather than the flow of material goods: they characterise the definition, analysis and management of information as "workflow management".
[src:business-logic-flaws/workflow] The transmission of information from one organization to another is a critical issue in this inter-organizational context and raises the importance of tasks they describe as "validation", "verification" and "data usage analysis".
[src:business-logic-flaws/workflow] A workflow management system (WfMS) is a software system for creating, executing, and monitoring a defined sequence of processes and tasks, with the broad goals of increasing productivity, reducing costs, becoming more agile, and improving information exchange within an organization.
[src:business-logic-flaws/workflow] These systems may be process-centric or data-centric, and they may also represent the workflow as graphical maps.
[src:business-logic-flaws/workflow] A workflow management system may also include an extensible interface so that external software applications can be integrated, providing support for wide area workflows that provide both faster response times and improved productivity.
[src:business-logic-flaws/workflow] The workflow concept is closely related to several fields in operations research and other areas that study the nature of work either quantitatively or qualitatively, such as artificial intelligence (in particular, the sub-discipline of AI planning) and ethnography.
[src:business-logic-flaws/workflow] The term "workflow" is more commonly used in particular industries like printing, as well as professional domains such as clinical laboratories.
[src:business-logic-flaws/workflow] It may have particular specialized meanings in these areas.
[src:business-logic-flaws/workflow] **Planning and scheduling**: A plan is a description of the logically necessary, partially ordered set of activities required to accomplish a specific goal given certain starting conditions.
[src:business-logic-flaws/workflow] A plan, when augmented with a schedule and resource allocation calculations, completely defines a particular *instance* of systematic processing in pursuit of a goal.
[src:business-logic-flaws/workflow] A workflow may be viewed as an often optimal or near-optimal realization of the mechanisms required to execute the same plan repeatedly.
[src:business-logic-flaws/workflow] **Flow control**: This is a control concept applied to workflows, to distinguish from static control of buffers of material or orders, to mean a more dynamic control of flow speed and flow volumes in motion and in process.
[src:business-logic-flaws/workflow] Such orientation to dynamic aspects is the basic foundation to prepare for more advanced job shop controls, such as just-in-time or just-in-sequence.
[src:business-logic-flaws/workflow] **In-transit visibility**: This monitoring concept applies to transported material as well as to work in process or work in progress, i.e., workflows.
[src:business-logic-flaws/workflow] Insurance claims processing is an example of an information-intensive, document-driven workflow.
[src:business-logic-flaws/workflow] Wikipedia editing can be modeled as a stochastic workflow.
[src:business-logic-flaws/workflow] The Getting Things Done system is a model of personal workflow management for information workers.
[src:business-logic-flaws/workflow] In software development, support and other industries, the concept of *follow-the-sun* describes a process of passing unfinished work across time zones.
[src:business-logic-flaws/workflow] In scientific experiments, the overall process (tasks and data flow) can be described as a directed acyclic graph (DAG).
[src:business-logic-flaws/workflow] This DAG is referred to as a workflow, e.g., Brain Imaging workflows.
[src:business-logic-flaws/workflow] In healthcare data analysis, a workflow can be identified or used to represent a sequence of steps that comprise a complex data analysis.
[src:business-logic-flaws/workflow] In service-oriented architectures, an application can be represented through an executable workflow, where different, possibly geographically distributed, service components interact to provide the corresponding functionality under the control of a workflow management system.
[src:business-logic-flaws/workflow] In shared services, an application can be in the practice of developing robotic process automation (called RPA or RPAAI for self-guided RPA 2.0 based on artificial intelligence) which results in the deployment of attended or unattended software agents to an organization's environment.
[src:business-logic-flaws/workflow] These software agents, or robots, are deployed to perform pre-defined structured and repetitive sets of business tasks or processes.
[src:business-logic-flaws/workflow] Artificial intelligence software robots are deployed to handle unstructured data sets and are deployed after performing and deploying robotic process automation.
[src:business-logic-flaws/workflow] Measurement: Many of the concepts used to measure scheduling systems in operations research are useful for measuring general workflows.
[src:business-logic-flaws/workflow] These include throughput, processing time, and other regular metrics.
[src:business-logic-flaws/workflow] Specialized connotations: The term "workflow" has specialized connotations in information technology, document management, and imaging.
[src:business-logic-flaws/workflow] Since 1993, one trade consortium specifically focused on workflow management and the interoperability of workflow management systems, the Workflow Management Coalition.
[src:business-logic-flaws/workflow] Scientific workflow systems: These found wide acceptance in the fields of bioinformatics and cheminformatics in the early 2000s, when they met the need for multiple interconnected tools that handle multiple data formats and large data quantities.
[src:business-logic-flaws/workflow] Also, the paradigm of scientific workflows resembles the well-established practice of Perl programming in life science research organizations, making this adoption a natural step towards more structured infrastructure setup.
[src:business-logic-flaws/workflow] Human-machine interaction: Several conceptualizations of mixed-initiative workflows have been studied, particularly in the military, where automated agents play roles just as humans do.
[src:business-logic-flaws/workflow] For innovative, adaptive, and collaborative human work, the techniques of human interaction management are required.
[src:business-logic-flaws/workflow] Workflow analysis: Workflow systems allow users to develop executable processes with no familiarity with formal programming concepts.
[src:business-logic-flaws/workflow] Automated workflow analysis techniques can help users analyze the properties of user workflows to conduct verification of certain properties before executing them, e.g., analyzing flow control or data flow.
[src:business-logic-flaws/workflow] Examples of tools based on formal analysis frameworks have been developed and used for the analysis of scientific workflows and can be extended to the analysis of other types of workflows.
[src:business-logic-flaws/workflow] Several workflow improvement theories have been proposed and implemented in the modern workplace.
[src:business-logic-flaws/workflow] Resource evaluation (both physical and human) is essential to evaluating hand-off points and creating smoother transitions between tasks.
[src:business-logic-flaws/workflow] A workflow can usually be described using formal or informal flow diagramming techniques and displays directed flows between processing steps.
[src:business-logic-flaws/workflow] Components can only be plugged together if the output of one previous (set of) component(s) is equal to the mandatory input requirements of the following component(s).
[src:business-logic-flaws/workflow] Thus, the essential description of a component actually comprises only input and output that are described fully in terms of data types and their meaning (semantics).
[src:business-logic-flaws/workflow] The algorithms' or rules' descriptions need only be included when there are several alternative ways to transform one type of input into one type of output – possibly with different accuracy, speed, etc.
[src:business-logic-flaws/workflow] When the components are non-local services that are invoked remotely via a computer network, such as Web services, developers must consider additional descriptors (such as QoS and availability).
[src:business-logic-flaws/workflow] A workflow application is a software application that automates a process or processes to some degree.
[src:business-logic-flaws/workflow] These processes are usually business-related but can be any process that requires a series of steps to be automated via software.
[src:business-logic-flaws/workflow] Some process steps may require human intervention, such as development and approval of custom text, but functions that can be automated should be handled by the application.
[src:business-logic-flaws/workflow] Advanced applications allow users to introduce new components into the operation.
